13 SECTION 5. There is hereby established a special commission to consist of 1 member of
14 the senate to be appointed by the president of the senate, who shall serve as co-chair, 1 member
15 of the house of representatives to be appointed by the speaker of the house of representatives,
16 who shall serve as co-chair, the commissioner of the department of public health, the
17 commissioner of the department of mental health, the commissioner of insurance, and the
18 director of Medicaid, or their designees, all of whom shall serve as ex officio members, and 13
19 persons to be appointed by the governor, 1 of whom shall be a representative from the
20 Massachusetts Gaming Commission, 1 of whom shall be a representative from the Office of
21 Problem Gambling Services, 1 of whom shall be a representative from the Massachusetts State
22 Lottery, 1 of whom shall be a representative from the Massachusetts Council on Gaming and
23 Health, 1 of whom shall be a representative from the Massachusetts Psychological Association
24 who shall be a psychologist, 1 of whom shall be a representative from the Massachusetts
25 Behavioral Health Partnership or a managed care organization or managed care entity
26 contracting with MassHealth, 3 of whom shall be representatives of the Massachusetts Medical
27 Society, including a family physician and a psychiatrist, 1 of whom shall be a representative
28 from the Massachusetts Association of Health Plans and 3 of whom shall be representatives from
29 commercial health insurance carriers or managed care organizations doing business in the
30 commonwealth, is hereby established for the purpose of making an investigation and study
31 relative to problem gambling, including, but not limited to: (i) an assessment of current research
32 on the subject and whether there exist evidence-based, best or promising practices on the
33 prevention, detection and treatment of problem gambling; (ii) a review of current policies and
34 practices with respect to medical screenings for problem gambling, including the frequency and
35 location of screenings and training of personnel administering the screenings, the availability of
2 of 4

36 reimbursement and issues relative to medical necessity and third-party coverage; (iii) provision
37 of assistance to the department of public health, other state agencies and organizations in the
38 development of professional and public educational materials and programs on problem
39 gambling, in the development of referral lists for problem gambling treatment, building on
40 existing resources and in the designation of authorized validated screening tools; (iv) provision
41 of assistance to the department of public health, other state agencies and organizations relative to
42 applications for federal funding to support efforts consistent with the mission and purpose of the
43 commission; and (v) any other matters that the commission considers relevant to the fulfillment
44 of its mission and purpose.
45 The commission shall provide guidance and advice to the governor, the general court and
46 the secretary of health and human services relative to current research on problem gambling
47 including, but not limited to, best and promising practices in the prevention, detection and
48 treatment of problem gambling and recommend policies, including legislation, to promote
49 greater public awareness, screening and treatment of problem gambling. The special commission
50 may conduct public hearings, forums or meetings to gather information and to raise awareness of
51 problem gambling, including the sponsorship of or participation in statewide or regional
52 conferences.
53 The commission shall hold its first meeting not later than 30 days after the effective date
54 of this act and shall meet not less frequently than monthly thereafter. The commission shall file
55 an annual report at the end of each state fiscal year with the governor and the clerks of the house
56 of representatives and the senate, who shall forward the same to the joint committee on public
57 health and the joint committee on ways and means, along with recommendations, if any, together
58 with drafts of legislation necessary to carry those recommendations into effect. The first such
3 of 4

59 report shall be due not later than June 30, 2026. The special commission may file such interim
60 reports and recommendations as it considers appropriate.
